One guiding principle for Sunday from the earliest days has been to give special emphasis to Australian films. The first film I reviewed on the very first program was Bruce Beresford's Puberty Blues, which broke new ground and was hugely popular. Mad Max II also appeared during those first months and was bracingly controversial.
I say this with the acknowledgement that unless we can promote intellectual growth in our youth, the system will certainly fail, in spite of its great intentions. As parents, the bulk of the responsibility falls to us. It will take time, probably an entire generation.
This makes it extraordinarily difficult to reconstruct the lives of the first Australian. But one archaeologist hopes to fill in some of the historical gaps by taking a new, much closer look at Aboriginal artefacts. Atwood describes these novels as speculative fiction rather than science fiction, arguing that her tales are speculations on the dangerous directions being taken by our current societies. These novels about the future are not about intergalactic space combat or otherplanetary alien creatures. Rather, they deal with all too identifiable human flaws and situations, with religious and social ideology evolving to frightening extremes.
